TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Dynamic Programming Approach to a Lot Size Scheduling Problem
AU  - Bomberger, Earl E.
Y1  - 1966/07/01
PY  - 1966
DA  - 1966/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.12.11.778
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.12.11.778
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 778
EP  - 784
VL  - 12
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The problem considered is that of scheduling the production of several different items over the same facility on a repetitive basis. The facility is such that only one item can be produced at a time; there is a setup cost and a setup time associated with producing each item; the demand rate for each item is known and constant over an infinite planning horizon, and all demand must be met. A dynamic programming solution is developed. This solution is applied to a sample problem, and the results are compared with pertinent bounds.
AB  - The problem considered is that of scheduling the production of several different items over the same facility on a repetitive basis. The facility is such that only one item can be produced at a time; there is a setup cost and a setup time associated with producing each item; the demand rate for each item is known and constant over an infinite planning horizon, and all demand must be met. A dynamic programming solution is developed. This solution is applied to a sample problem, and the results are compared with pertinent bounds.
